 commodifying tourist gaze. Drawing on literary narratives, educational texts, newspaper articles, tourist materials, films, popular songs, posters, photographs, and cartoons, Zerubavel reveals the complexities and contradictions that mark Israeli society's semiotics of space in relation to the Middle East, and the central role of the "besieged island" trope in Israeli culture and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDesertsxSymbolic aspectszIsrael. 0aSemioticszIsrael. 4aBedouins. 4aDesert. 4aHebrew culture. 4aIsrael. 4aJewish memory. 4aMiddle Eastern conflict. 4aNegev. 4aenvironmentalism. 4aspace. 4atourism. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360760640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607606423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503607606.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles